ST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fychan","type":"LAST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Madoc","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."],"variants":[{"name":"Madog","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Madoc ap Hywel Fychan was born about 1230, in Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Hywel \"Howell the Less\"  Vychan ap Llewellyn, was 22 and his mother, Sara le Sore, was 48. He had at least 1 son with Lwerdd Verch Lewys."},"et":{"ABT 1230–":"umbes 1230–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1252–1278":"1252–1278","1210–1243":"1210–1243","1183–Female":"1183–Surnud","ABT 1230":"umbes 1230","1278":"1278","1243":"1243","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1183":"1183","about 1252":"umbes 1252","Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Presteigne, Llythyfnwg, Radnorshire, Wales":"Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1230–":"noin 1230–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1252–1278":"1252–1278","1210–1243":"1210–1243","1183–Female":"1183–Kuollut","ABT 1230":"noin 1230","1278":"1278","1243":"1243","1210":"1210","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1183":"1183","about 1252":"noin 1252","Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire